title: For Sale/Trade:  Very Rare Demro TAC-1 Carbine 9mm
postcontent: ***IF YOU SEE THIS AD THEN IT IS STILL AVAILABLE***Up for sale or trade is an extremely rare piece of firearms history.There are two on gunbroker, one for $2495 starting bid and has both caliber conversions, one for $1495 starting bid in 45acp, and only 1 on all of Armslist for $900, it is in 45acp and is missing handgrip panels and no magazines, and one is available at checkpointcharlies for $895.One of the very few firearms that fires from an open bolt and is legal to own without a tax stamp.It uses easy to find STEN magazines and has integrated muzzlebrake.It has 3 safeties which block the sear from releasing the bolt: 1.) 3 number combination lock; 2.) Pistol grip safety and 3.) Manual lever safety.It also has a detachable Walnut wooden butt stock that has a built in magazine loader.A true one of kind opportunity to own an extremely rare weapon in preban '82 open bolt semi-auto configuration! It is a very uncommon and rather odd firearm resembling a Thompson submachine gun.This rare weapon turns up every so often in the hands of dedicated open bolt collectors.The original Fox Carbine open bolt assault carbine was manufactured by TRI-C, Inc. in Manchester, Connecticut for only two short years in 1974-1976 due to a fire that completely destroyed the factory in April 1976In 1977, the rights were sold to Dean Machine Products Incorporated (DEMRO PRODUCTS INCORPORATED) in Manchester, Connecticut.DEMRO continued to produce and sell these firearms until the early 1980's only because the BATF made a ruling in 1982 that all semi-automatic open-bolt weapons weretoo easily and readily convertible to full automatic fire. Therefore, such weapons manufactured after the date of this ruling are classed and controlled as fully automatic weapons;(weapons manufactured prior to the ruling are grandfathered and are still considered semi-automatic).This weapon is considered semi-auto only and is legal to own in most states. This rifle can switch between 9mm and 45acp IF you have the 45acp barrel,bolt and mag well insert I do not have the 45acp barrel,bolt or magwell insert.My rifle comes with 3 sten mags. One mag has problems, probably a weak spring, other mags work perfectly.I am asking $800 cash or best offer or trade.

postcontent: This bolt gun started its life as a 700 ADL Varmint (heavy barrel, blued) with a synthetic camo theme stock.  The stock was swapped out for a Bell & Carlson Medalist in a color called gray w/black web.  As part of the stock swap, I did a BDL conversion and added the drop out floor plate.  The next order of business was to put a Millett 4-16X50 scope (illuminated reticle) on top.  The trigger was swapped out by a Remington authorized gunsmith in Burley as part of the recall and now has the adjustable X mark pro.  I've not put it on a guage, but it's breaking where a bench gun should.  I've done some load development and have had the best luck with the Hornady A-max bullets, but I really haven't put enough time into the Sierra MK's to see if there is a recipe there that would compete.  I do have about 60 MK experiment rounds loaded that I could include if interested.  I also have 40 A-max rounds loaded that would be included.I'm willing to sell for $800 without the scope or ammo or $1100 with the scope and ammo. I will insist on seeing proof of Idaho residency and getting a signed bill of sale.  If you are from out of state, you will need to pay an FFL transfer fee at one of the local gunshops.Price for everything $1100: This would include the gun, scope, and 100 rounds mentioned above.  I do have the original box for the scope.I have some sealed boxes of 168 gr Sierra MK and 168 gr Hornady A-max bullets that we could add into the deal for a bit more cash if you want to do some of your own load development.Email if interested.I'm not really looking for any trades right now, just wanting cash for some other projects.
